Pearsons Correlation Coefficient: measuring a relationship between quantitative variables

A statistic to measure the linear association between variables

For two quantitative variables, we use the sample Pearson correlation coefficient to compare the strength and direction of a potential linear association. In R, we use the cor() function.

  • You can use cor() inside a summarize() dplyr pipe:
# cor() function for Pearson's correlation coefficient.
skincancer %>%
    summarise(
        corr_lat = cor(mortality, latitude),
        corr_long = cor(mortality, longitude)
    )
  • Alternatively, we can pass a data frame with many quantitative variables into the cor function and return a matrix of correlations. Try selecting just latitude, longitude, and mortality from our data frame, and pass that into cor().
skincancer %>%
    select(mortality, longitude, latitude) %>%
    cor()
##            mortality   longitude    latitude
## mortality  1.0000000 -0.14618812 -0.82451779
## longitude -0.1461881  1.00000000  0.09897372
## latitude  -0.8245178  0.09897372  1.00000000

Sample statistic \(r\) vs.population parameter \(\rho\)

Lets generate some population level data that is correlated:

# This creates a population where two variables (x and y) are 
# strongly correlated.  Your correlation will be slightly different.
set.seed(553311)
test_x<-rnorm(5000, 60, 15)
test_y<-1.3*test_x + rnorm(5000,0,15)
paste("Population Correlation:", round(cor(test_x,test_y),3))
## [1] "Population Correlation: 0.799"

So what happens when we take a sample?

ind<-sample(1:5000,35)
ggplot()+
    geom_point(aes(x = test_x, y= test_y),
               color='gray',alpha = .5)+
    geom_point(aes(x = test_x[ind], y= test_y[ind]),
             color='blue')+theme_bw()+
    annotate(geom="text", x = 20, y = 160, label=paste("rho = ", round(cor(test_x,test_y),3)),cex=5)+
    annotate(geom="text", x = 20, y = 140, label=paste("r = ", round(cor(test_x[ind],test_y[ind]),3)),cex=5,color='blue')+
    labs(x = "x-values",y="y-values",title="Comparing the population correlation to a sample correlation.")

Does \(r\) appear to generally fall near \(\rho\)?

Shiny Visualization

Hypothesis test for \(\rho\)

Lets consider our skincancer data once more. We suspect that as we move higher in the northern hemisphere (i.e.Latitude increases), the skin cancer mortality will decrease.

Test the claim that the correlation between these variables is greater than or equal to zero.

(Why are we testing a claim we dont believe is true? So we can reject it!)

Hypotheses

  • \(H_0: \rho \geq 0\)
  • \(H_1: \rho < 0\)

We can run a hypothesis test for a claim about the population Pearson correlation coefficient, \(\rho\), using the R-command cor.test(). As with all hypothesis tests, its a good idea to write out your hypothesis first.

  • \(H_0\): our population correlation coefficient is greater than or equal to zero
  • \(H_1\): our population correlation coefficient is less than zero
#Place code here.
skincancer %>%
    with(
        cor.test(latitude, mortality,
                 alternative = "less")
    ) %>% tidy() %>%
    select(estimate, p.value)

With a \(P\)-value (0.000bunch zero later 165) below a significance of 5%, we reject the null hypothesis. We have sufficient evidence to suggest that correlation is negative at the population level.

What about longitude?

skincancer %>%
    with(
        cor.test(longitude, mortality,
                 alternative = "less")
    ) %>% tidy() %>%
    select(estimate, p.value)

For longitude, we failed to reject the null hypothesis that the correlation coefficient is greater than or equal to zero.

A very important point

Even finding a statistically significant correlation does not mean that you have found a causal relationship between your variables.

  • Ice cream sales and the number of shark attacks have a significant positive correlation, but it would be silly to believe that ice cream is causing more shark attacks.

  • This webiste gives a nice, high-level summary of this idea.

Penguins again?! OK, fine we love penguins.

Researchers suspect that penguins with longer flippers also tend to have longer bills. How should we set our hypotheses?

  • \(H_0\): rho <= 0
  • \(H_1\): rho > 0

rho: is the pop. level correlation coefficient between flipper length and bil length.

Create a visual!

# Place code here.
penguins %>%
    filter(!is.na(flipper_length_mm),
           !is.na(bill_length_mm)) -> penguins1

ggplot(data = penguins1,
       aes(x = flipper_length_mm, y = bill_length_mm))+
    geom_point()

Summarize?

penguins1 %>%
    summarise(
        corr = cor(flipper_length_mm, bill_length_mm),
        sample_size = n()
    )

Run the hypothesis test:

# Place code here.
penguins1 %>%
    with(
        cor.test(flipper_length_mm, bill_length_mm,
                 alternative = "greater")
    ) %>% tidy() %>%
    select(estimate, p.value)

Our \(P\)-value is basically zero, so less than a significance of 0.05, so we have evidence that there is a positive correlation between flipper length and bill lenght.

Yeah, but what is our best guess for the correlation coefficient at the population level?

# Place code here.
penguins1 %>%
    with(
        cor.test(flipper_length_mm, bill_length_mm),
        conf.level = .97
        # remove the alternative argument when 
        # doing a confidence interval.
    ) %>% tidy() %>%
    select(conf.low, estimate, conf.high)

The complete.cases() command will return a logical vector, with which we can filter, where TRUE indicates that row doesnt have any NA-values. Its a quick way to avoid dealing with NAs, but you could have better sample sizes if you filter out NAs by variable instead.

penguins_complete<-penguins %>%
    filter(complete.cases(penguins))
nrow(penguins_complete)
## [1] 333
# Notice we had more data for our analysis above than we would
# if we used penguins_complete
nrow(penguins1)
## [1] 342
nrow(penguins)
## [1] 344

Is there an associate between body mass and flipper length?

Just to demonstrate a two-tailed test, lets test the following hypotheses:

\(\rho:\) the population correlation coefficient between body_mass and flipper_length_mm.

\(H_0: \rho = 0\)

\(H_1: \rho \neq 0\).

Visual and summary:

penguins_complete %>%
    summarise(sample_size = n(),
              corr = cor(body_mass_g, flipper_length_mm))
penguins_complete %>%
    ggplot(data = .,
            aes(x = body_mass_g, flipper_length_mm))+
    geom_point(color='purple') + 
    theme_bw()

Lets run our hypothesis test:

penguins_complete %>%
    with(
        cor.test(body_mass_g, flipper_length_mm)
    ) %>% tidy() %>% select(estimate,p.value)

Our \(P\)-value is well below a standard significance level of 0.05, so we have evidence to suggest there is a correlation between body mass and flipper length for penguins.

Follow-up questions (for those interested)

Q: Which relationship is stronger, flipper length with bill length, or flipper length with body mass?

Without doing something more complicated, we could look at confidence interval estimates for each correlation coefficient and try to compare:

penguins_complete %>%
    with(
        cor.test(bill_length_mm, flipper_length_mm)
    ) %>% tidy() %>% select(conf.low, conf.high)
penguins_complete %>%
    with(
        cor.test(body_mass_g, flipper_length_mm)
    ) %>% tidy() %>% select(conf.low, conf.high)

Notice that these confidence intervals do not overlap at all!

  • The highest estimated correlation coefficient for bill length and flipper length is 0.71, while the lowest estimated correlation coefficient for body mass and flipper length is 0.844.
  • This suggests that at the population level, the relationship between body mass and flipper length is the stronger one.

Q: What if we consider the species in this analysis?

penguins_complete %>%
    ggplot(data = .,
            aes(x = body_mass_g, flipper_length_mm, color = species))+
    geom_point() + 
    theme_bw()

penguins_complete %>%
    group_by(species) %>%
    summarise(sample_size = n(),
              corr = cor(body_mass_g,flipper_length_mm)
              )

The visual and summary table suggest that, at least on the data, this relationship has varying strength for different species. We would have to do some inference for this to make any claims about the population trend, but that would require techniques beyond this course!
